{"info": {"author": "Toby Isaac", "author_email": "tisaac@cc.gatech.edu", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["Intended Audience :: Science/Research", "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Natural Language :: English", "Operating System :: OS Independent", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Topic :: Scientific/Engineering :: Mathematics"], "description": "# `recursivenodes`: Recursive, parameter-free, explicitly defined interpolation nodes for simplices\n\nThis package includes one module level function, `recursive_nodes()`, which returns\nnodes for polynomial interpolation on the simplex in arbitrary dimensions.\n\nThe nodes have a few nice properties: they are explicitly constructed and fully\nsymmetric, and their traces on edges are Lobatto-Gauss-Legendre nodes (or any\nother node set you wish to use).  Among explicitly constructed nodes, they\nappear to have the best interpolation properties.  You can find more details in\nthe [documentation](https://tisaac.gitlab.io/recursivenodes).\n\n## Requirements:\n\n- Only `numpy` and `scipy` are needed for `recursive_nodes()`.\n- Testing requires `coverage`, `pytest` and `matplotlib`.\n- Building documentation additionally requires `sphinx`, `sphinxcontrib-bibtex`, and `sphinxcontrib-tikz`.\n\n\n", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://tisaac.gitlab.io/recursivenodes/", "keywords": "", "license": "MIT", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "recursivenodes", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/recursivenodes/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/recursivenodes/", "project_urls": {"Bug Tracker": "https://gitlab.com/tisaac/recursivenodes/issues", "Homepage": "https://tisaac.gitlab.io/recursivenodes/", "Source Code": "https://gitlab.com/tisaac/recursivenodes/"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/recursivenodes/0.1.0/", "requires_dist": ["numpy", "scipy", "matplotlib ; extra == 'all'", "pytest ; extra == 'all'", "coverage ; extra == 'all'", "sphinx ; extra == 'all'", "sphinxcontrib-bibtex ; extra == 'all'", "sphinxcontrib-tikz ; extra == 'all'", "matplotlib ; extra == 'doc'", "sphinx ; extra == 'doc'", "sphinxcontrib-bibtex ; extra == 'doc'", "sphinxcontrib-tikz ; extra == 'doc'", "matplotlib ; extra == 'test'", "pytest ; extra == 'test'", "coverage ; extra == 'test'"], "requires_python": ">=3.6", "summary": "Recursively defined interpolation nodes for the simplex", "version": "0.1.0", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <h1><code>recursivenodes</code>: Recursive, parameter-free, explicitly defined interpolation nodes for simplices</h1>\n<p>This package includes one module level function, <code>recursive_nodes()</code>, which returns\nnodes for polynomial interpolation on the simplex in arbitrary dimensions.</p>\n<p>The nodes have a few nice properties: they are explicitly constructed and fully\nsymmetric, and their traces on edges are Lobatto-Gauss-Legendre nodes (or any\nother node set you wish to use).  Among explicitly constructed nodes, they\nappear to have the best interpolation properties.  You can find more details in\nthe <a href=\"https://tisaac.gitlab.io/recursivenodes\" rel=\"nofollow\">documentation</a>.</p>\n<h2>Requirements:</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Only <code>numpy</code> and <code>scipy</code> are needed for <code>recursive_nodes()</code>.</li>\n<li>Testing requires <code>coverage</code>, <code>pytest</code> and <code>matplotlib</code>.</li>\n<li>Building documentation additionally requires <code>sphinx</code>, <code>sphinxcontrib-bibtex</code>, and <code>sphinxcontrib-tikz</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 6491860, "releases": {"0.1.0": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "4354d3f26cc7fe76b701aa05de2f8f7f", "sha256": "d3ae6ed94d2f476e3b00c8f869b858ed9e8f78697290338233dd13abdeb7a13b"}, "downloads": -1, "filename